MEI believes that maker education is critical to preparing students for success in college, career, and life. To achieve its mission, MEI develops programs, tools, and resources to support educators in integrating making into their classrooms and schools.  History   The Maker Education Initiative was founded in 2012 by Dale Dougherty, founder of MAKE magazine and Maker Faire, and Mark Hatch, founder of TechShop. The organization was initially funded by grants from the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation, the Grable Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.  Programs   MEI operates several programs to support maker education in K-12 schools. These include:   FabLearn Fellowship: This program provides funding and professional development opportunities for K-12 educators interested in integrating making into their classrooms. Fellows participate in a year-long program that includes online courses, summer workshops, mentoring, and networking opportunities.   FabSchools Network: This program supports schools in building sustainable maker education programs. Schools in the FabSchools Network receive training, resources, and ongoing support from MEI staff and FabLearn Fellows.   FabFoundation: The FabFoundation is

Input:  Bootleg_Series_Volume_1:_The_Quine_Tapes  genre  Rock_music ,  Bootleg_Series_Volume_1:_The_Quine_Tapes  precededBy  Squeeze_(The_Velvet_Underground_album) ,  Squeeze_(The_Velvet_Underground_album)  precededBy  Andy_Warhol's_Velvet_Underground_Featuring_Nico   Output:   When I was growing up, my mom used to make this dish for us at least once a week. It was one of our favorite meals. The original recipe calls for ground beef, but I decided to use ground turkey instead to lighten it up a bit. This is a very simple recipe, but the flavors are so good!  In a large skillet, cook ground turkey over medium heat until browned, stirring often to break up meat. Drain off any excess grease.  Stir in tomato sauce, water, chili powder, cumin, salt, and pepper. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat; simmer, uncovered, for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally.  Serve over hot cooked rice. Sprinkle each serving with shredded cheese and chopped green onion. Input:  Liselotte_Grschebina  birthPlace  Karlsruhe ,  Liselotte_Grschebina  nationality  Israel ,  Liselotte_Grschebina  training  School_of_Applied_Arts_in_Stuttgart ,  Karlsruhe  country  Germany ,  Israel  language  Modern_Hebrew   Output:   The Difference Between a Fuse and a Circuit Breaker  Posted on September 15, 2021 September 15, 2021 by David Smith  Fuses and circuit breakers are both essential components of electrical systems for protecting circuits from overloads and short circuits. However, they differ in several ways, including how they function, their durability, and where they are used. In this article, we will discuss the differences between fuses and circuit breakers.  What is a Fuse?  A fuse is a safety device designed to protect electrical circuits from damage caused by excessive current flow. It consists of a strip of metal or semiconductor material enclosed in a non-conductive casing. When the current flowing through the fuse exceeds its rated capacity, the fuse element melts, breaking the circuit and preventing further current flow.  Fuses come in various types, such as cartridge, blade, glass, and ceramic, with different amperage ratings. They are commonly used in low-voltage circuits, such as those found in homes, cars, and appliances.  What is a Circuit Breaker?  A circuit breaker is another type of safety device used to protect electrical circuits from overloads and short circuits. Unlike fuses, which are disposable, circuit breakers can be reset and used again after an overload

The project was launched in 2014 with funding from the USDA's National Institute of Food and Agriculture (NIFA), and is led by UC ANR's Nutrition Policy Institute (NPI). NPI is part of UC ANR's Strategic Initiative for Healthy Families and Communities, which seeks to improve the health and well-being of all Californians through research, education, and outreach.  The Local Food Systems Project aims to increase access to healthy, locally produced food; support economic development in rural and urban communities; and build partnerships between producers and consumers. To achieve these goals, the project focuses on four key areas:  Capacity building: Providing training, resources, and technical assistance to local food system stakeholders, including farmers, farmers market managers, school garden coordinators, and others.  Research and evaluation: Conducting research to better understand the impact of local food systems on health,

In a statement to CNBC, NBCUniversal said, "We're excited that American fans will enjoy The Office exclusively on Peacock in the U.S., and that international fans will be able to enjoy it on Netflix for many years to come." A: You can use Series.nunique() with .all():  df['column'].nunique().all()  For example:  df = pd.DataFrame({'column': [1, 2, 3, 4]})  print(df['column'].nunique())  # 4  print(df['column'].nunique().all())  # True  df = pd.DataFrame({'column': [1, 2, 3, 4, 4]})  print(df['column'].nunique())  # 4  print(df['column'].nunique().all())  # False

PersonX is always the subject of the event. You have to determine whether the Head happens before the Tail or not. Classify your answers into "Yes" and "No". The phrase may also contain "___", a placeholder that can be an object, a person, and/or an action.  Example Input: Head: PersonX accomplishes the mission<sep>Tail: PersonX gets a promotion  Example Output: Yes  Example Input: Head: PersonX accepts another offer<sep>Tail: PersonX has to buy a new suit  Example Output: Yes  Example Input: Head: PersonX achieves PersonX's aims<sep>Tail: PersonX celebrates their success  Example Output:  Yes

(Python) I have tried creating a function that takes a list of numbers as an argument and returns the sum of the squares of all the elements in the list. Here is my attempt:  ```python  def sum_of_squares(numbers):      total = 0      for num in numbers:          total += num ** 2      return total  print(sum_of_squares([1, 2, 3, 4]))  ```  However, when I run this code, it works correctly and returns the expected output of `100`. Is there anything wrong with my function or am I missing something?  A: There is nothing wrong with your function. It calculates the sum of the squares of all the elements in the list correctly. The issue might be with the environment where you are running the code or some other unrelated problem.  Your function can be shortened using Python's built-in sum function with a lambda expression:  def sum_of_squares(numbers):      return sum(map(lambda x: x**2, numbers))  A: Your function is correct. However, you can optimize it by using the built-in

Home > Resources > News > New Year, New Job – How to Make a Successful Career Change  New Year, New Job – How to Make a Successful Career Change  The start of a new year often prompts people to reflect on their lives and make changes for the better. One common resolution is to switch careers, but making such a significant change can be daunting. Here are some tips to help you make a successful career change in 2023.  1. Identify what you want  Before embarking on a career change, it's essential to understand what you're looking for in a new career. Consider your values, interests, strengths, and weaknesses. Think about the aspects of your current job that you enjoy and those that you don't. Write down your ideal work environment, hours, salary, and opportunities for growth.  2. Research potential careers  Once you have a clear idea of what you want in a new career, research potential options that align with your preferences. Look into job descriptions, requirements, salaries, and growth potential. Talk to people working in these fields to get first-hand insights into the day-to-day realities of the job.  3. Assess your transferable skills  Many skills are transferable

Input:  English_Without_Tears  musicComposer  Nicholas_Brodszky   Output:   Home > News > Industry News > China's Largest Solar Power Plant Comes Online  China's Largest Solar Power Plant Comes Online  Post Time:Dec 08,2014Classify:Industry NewsView:57  China's largest solar power plant came online last week in the northwestern province of Qinghai, according to state-run news agency Xinhua.  The Longyangxia Dam Solar Park is located near the Longyangxia Dam on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, and has a total installed capacity of 850 megawatts (MW).  According to Xinhua, the park consists of 4 million photovoltaic panels, covering an area of 8 square kilometers (3.1 square miles). The facility is expected to generate 1.1 billion kilowatt-hours (kWh) of electricity per year, enough to meet the needs of more than 800,000 households.  The Longyangxia Dam Solar Park is also the world's first large-scale solar power plant built on a dam reservoir. The water body helps cool the photovoltaic panels, improving their efficiency by up to 25 percent, according to Xinhua.  Source: http://www.chinadialogue.

By John Manganaro  The U.S. Department of Labor (DOL) has released its long-anticipated proposal to reconsider the fiduciary rule and related exemptions. According to the DOL, this new BIC exemption will apply to investment advice fiduciaries providing investment advice to retirement investors. The Child and Adolescent Mental Health Service (CAMHS) is part of Northumberland, Tyne and Wear NHS Foundation Trust (NTW) and provides specialist assessment and treatment for children and young people with emotional, behavioural and mental health problems.  The new service, which covers North Tyneside, will enable young people to access support closer to home through a network of community-based clinics.  As well as providing one-to-one therapy, the team also offers family therapy, group work and social skills programmes.  Clinical Lead for CAMHS, Dr Paula Macdonald, said: "We know that early intervention can make a real difference to young people's mental health and wellbeing.  "Our aim is to build resilience so that young people have the skills and confidence to cope with life's ups and downs."  Referrals to the service can be made by GPs, school nurses, educational psychologists, social workers and other health professionals.  For more information about the service, visit www.ntw.nhs.uk/camhs  If you

Input:  Andrew_Rayel  genre  Trance_music ,  Andrew_Rayel  associatedBand/associatedMusicalArtist  "Armin Van Buuren, Bobina, Mark Sixma, Jonathan Mendelsohn, Christian Burns, Jwaydan, Alexander Popov, Jano, Alexandre Bergheau, Jonny Rose, Sylvia Tosun, Lira Yin, Alexandra Badoi"   Output:   Q: How do I create a list of all occurrences of two specific characters in a string? I want to create a list of all occurrences of two specific characters in a string. For example, if the string is "Hello World", the output should be [(0, 'H'), (1, 'e'), (2, 'l'), (3, ' '), (4, 'W'), (5, 'o'), (6, 'r'), (7, 'l'), (8, 'd'), (9, '\n')]. The first element of each tuple represents the index of the character in the string, and the second element represents the character itself.  A: You can use enumerate with a list comprehension to achieve this:  string = "Hello World"  result = [(i, char) for i, char in enumerate(string)]  This creates an iterator over the indices and characters of the string, which is then converted into a list using a list comprehension.  To only include specific characters, you can filter the result:  specific_chars = {'H', 'W'}  result = [(i, char) for i, char in enumerate(string) if char in specific_chars]  In this case, the result will be:  [(0, 'H'), (4, 'W')]

Input:  Sludge_metal  musicSubgenre  Southern_sludge   Output:   Q: How do I get the first letter of each word in a string? I have a string like this:  string str = "hello my name is john doe";  How do I get the first letter of each word in the string?  The output should be:  h m n i j d  A: Use LINQ:  string str = "hello my name is john doe";  string result = string.Join(" ", str.Split(' ').Select(x => x[0]));  A: Try this:  string str = "hello my name is john doe";  string[] words = str.Split(' ');  StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();  for (int i = 0; i < words.Length; i++)  {      sb.Append(words[i][0]);      if (i != words.Length - 1)      {          sb.Append(' ');      }  }  string result = sb.ToString();  A: You can also use String.Concat() with Enumerable.Select():  string str = "hello my name is john doe";  string result = string.Concat(str.Split(' ').Select(x => x[0]));  A: You can split the string by space and then iterate over the array

Specifically, this study examines the mediating role of employee engagement between HRM practices and organizational performance. This study was conducted using a quantitative approach with a survey research design. The population of this study consists of employees working in private companies in Jakarta. Data were collected through self-administered questionnaires distributed to 350 respondents. A total of 324 usable questionnaires were returned, resulting in a response rate of 92.57%. The data were analyzed using descriptive statistics, correlation analysis, and structural equation modeling (SEM). The results show that HRM practices have a significant positive effect on employee engagement and organizational performance. Employee engagement partially mediates the relationship between HRM practices and organizational performance. These findings suggest that HRM practices can improve organizational performance by enhancing employee engagement. Thus, organizations should focus on implementing effective HRM practices to engage their employees and ultimately achieve better organizational performance.

Emgality is a monoclonal antibody that binds to the calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP) ligand, which is believed to play a role and is considered a marker in the process of migraine attacks. "Today's approval provides another option for the preventive treatment of migraine in adults," said Eric Bastings, M.D., deputy director of the Division of Neurology Products in the FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research. "The FDA continues to work efficiently to review new treatments for migraine to give patients with this disabling condition more options." The efficacy of Emgality was established in three randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled studies in patients with a history of episodic or chronic migraine. In all three studies, patients treated with Emgality experienced statistically significant reductions in monthly migraine days compared to placebo. The most common adverse reactions reported in at least 5% of patients

Lying off the north-western coast of the European mainland, it includes the island of Great Britain (the name of which is also loosely applied to the whole country), the north-eastern part of the island of Ireland, and many smaller islands. Northern Ireland is the only part of the UK that shares a land border with another sovereign statethe Republic of Ireland. Apart from this land border, the UK is surrounded by the Atlantic Ocean, with the North Sea to its east, the English Channel to its south and the Celtic Sea to its south-south-west, giving it the 12th-longest coastline in the world. The Irish Sea lies between Great Britain and Ireland. With an area of , the UK is the 78th-largest sovereign state in the world and the 11th-largest in Europe. It is also the 21st-most populous country, with an estimated 65.1 million inhabitants. Input:  Olga_Bondareva  birthPlace  Leningrad,_USSR ,  Olga_Bondareva  birthDate  1937-04-27   Output:   Home > News > featured news > Fujitsu Introduces New Quantum-Inspired Digital Annealer Solving Capabilities for Optimization Problems  Fujitsu Introduces New Quantum-Inspired Digital Annealer Solving Capabilities for Optimization Problems  Fujitsu | December 08, 2022 | Read time : 03:00 min  Fujitsu Limited and Fujitsu Laboratories Ltd. today announced the development of new optimization solving capabilities for their quantum-inspired digital annealer technology. With these enhancements, users can now solve more complex combinatorial optimization problems by incorporating multiple constraints into a single problem instance. This is expected to significantly expand the range of real-world applications where the technology can deliver tangible benefits.  Digital annealing is a computational method inspired by the physics phenomenon of thermal annealing, which is used to find the lowest energy state (optimal solution) in complex combinatorial optimization problems. It is particularly effective at solving large-scale NP-hard problems that are difficult to solve using classical algorithms.  The new enhancement allows users to incorporate multiple constraints into a single problem instance, making it possible to solve problems that were previously too complex to tackle with existing digital annealing technologies. This includes problems that require finding the optimal solution within a restricted search space defined by multiple constraints.

Input:  Bootleg_Series_Volume_1:_The_Quine_Tapes  recordLabel  Universal_Music_Group   Output:   The following article contains an answer for the question: What is the first name of the person whose father was a peripatetic music teacher? , can you please find it?   Edmund Sharpe was born on 31 October 1809 at Brook Cottage, Brook Street in Knutsford, Cheshire, the first child of Francis and Martha Sharpe.  His father, a peripatetic music teacher and organist at Knutsford parish church, came from Stamford in Lincolnshire.  At the time of marriage his wife, Martha Whittaker, was on the staff of an academy for young ladies, Belgrave Lodge Girls' School, in Bath, Somerset. During his childhood in Knutsford, the young Edmund played with Elizabeth Stevenson, the future Mrs Gaskell. In 1812 the Sharpe family moved across town from Over Knutsford to a farm in Nether Knutsford named Heathside, when Francis Sharpe then worked as both farmer and music teacher.  Edmund was initially educated by his parents, but by 1821 he was attending a school in Knutsford.  Two years later he was a boarder at a school near Runcorn, and in 1826 he attended a school in Warrington. Edmund's father died suddenly in November 1823, aged 48, and

Porsche has announced pricing for its all-new 2013 Cayenne Diesel, which is set to go on sale in the U.S. this November.  The new Cayenne Diesel starts at $59,695, excluding a $995 destination charge, making it the most affordable model in the Cayenne lineup. However, it's still significantly more expensive than some of its diesel rivals, such as the Mercedes-Benz ML350 BlueTEC, which starts at just $49,900.  The new Cayenne Diesel features a turbocharged 3.0-liter V-6 diesel engine producing 240 horsepower and 406 pound-feet of torque. The engine is mated to an eight-speed Tiptronic S automatic transmission and sends power to all four wheels via Porsche's Active All-Wheel Drive system.  Acceleration from 0-60 mph takes just 7.2 seconds, while top speed is rated at 136 mph. Fuel economy

Under the proposed rule, a crewmember would have the authority to remove a passenger who is intoxicated; assaults, threatens, intimidates, or interferes with, or attempts to assault, threaten, intimidate, or interfere with, a crewmember; or engages in threatening, offensive, or disorderly conduct or fails to comply with a crewmember's instructions related to operation or safety of the aircraft. The proposal would also require airlines to develop and implement policies outlining how they will address passengers who violate these rules.  In addition, the NPRM proposes to require airlines to disclose in their contracts of carriage that passengers may be denied boarding or removed from a flight for violent, threatening, or disruptive behavior.  Comments on the NPRM must be received within 60 days after publication in the Federal Register. I am working on a program that calculates the mean, median, mode, range, variance, and standard deviation of a set of numbers entered by the user. However, when the user does not enter any numbers and just presses enter, the program freezes. How can I fix this issue so that the program moves on to the next calculation without freezing?  Here is my code:  numbers = []  count = 0  while True:      num = int(input("Enter a number: "))      if num == 0:          break      else:          numbers.append(num)          count += 1  mean = sum(numbers)/count  median = sorted(numbers)[len(numbers)//2]  mode = max(set(numbers), key=numbers.count)  range = max(numbers) - min(numbers)  variance = sum([(x - mean) ** 2 for x in numbers]) / count  standard_deviation = math.sqrt(variance)  print(f"Mean: {mean}")  print(f"Median: {median}")  print(f"Mode: {mode}")  print(f"Range: {range}")  print(

Another factor is the design of the home itself. For example, a single storey home with four bedrooms will generally cost less to build than a double storey home with the same number of bedrooms.  The quality of materials and finishes you choose will also affect the overall cost of your new home. It's important to carefully consider all these factors when budgeting for your new home.

Bolt joins American Century Investments from Principal Financial Group, where he served as senior vice president and director of institutional sales and relationship management. According to the report, the investigation began last year after Macmillan, HarperCollins, Penguin, Simon & Schuster and Hachette switched to an agency pricing model for their e-books sold through Apple's iBookstore. This pricing model allowed the publishers to set the price of their e-books, rather than letting retailers like Amazon set the price.  Prior to the switch, Amazon had dominated the e-book market by selling e-books at a loss in order to increase sales of its Kindle e-readers. When the publishers adopted the agency pricing model, they were able to charge higher prices for their e-books across all platforms, including Amazon's Kindle store.  In response, Amazon temporarily removed the buy buttons from Macmillan's e-books, preventing customers from purchasing those titles until the publisher backed down.  The DOJ's investigation is said to be focused on whether Apple colluded with the publishers to raise e-book prices. In addition to Apple and the five publishers mentioned above, the DOJ is also reportedly looking into potential collusion between Barnes & Noble and several smaller publishers.  Apple did not immediately respond to our request for comment.

Academic journal article The Journal of Social, Political, and Economic Studies  The Impact of Globalization on Developing Countries: A Critical Review  By Nwankwo, Chijioke Uchechukwu  Globalization is a multidimensional concept that has been defined differently by different scholars. For instance, Stiglitz (2006) defines globalization as "the increasing integration of national economies around the world through trade, capital flows, migration, and diffusion of technology and information" (p. 1). In contrast, Held et al. (1999) define globalization as "the widening, intensifying, and speeding up of global interconnectedness in four key dimensions: economics, politics, culture, and ecology" (p. 18). These definitions suggest that globalization is a process characterized by economic, political, cultural, and ecological interactions among nations across the globe. While some countries have benefited immensely from globalization, other countries have not fared so well. This paper examines the impact of globalization on developing countries.  Globalization and Its Dimensions  Globalization can be traced back to the sixteenth century when Europeans

It has been parodied, mocked, and used as an example of how not to start a story. But where did it come from, and what does it really mean?  The phrase "It was a dark and stormy night" first appeared in print in 1830 in the novel "Paul Clifford" by Edward Bulwer-Lytton. The full opening line reads, "It was a dark and stormy night; the rain fell in torrents, except at occasional intervals, when it was checked by a violent gust of wind which swept up the streets (for it is in London that our scene occurs), rattling along the housetops, and fiercely agitating the scanty flame of the lamps that struggled against the darkness."  Bulwer-Lytton was a prolific writer, producing over 70 novels, plays, and poems during his lifetime. While he enjoyed popularity during his time, his work is not as well-remembered today. However, the opening line from "Paul Clifford" has become a cultural punchline, often used to mock overly dramatic or clichéd writing.  Despite its negative connotations, the opening line serves its purpose within the context of the novel. The stormy night sets the

Input:  Bananaman  starring  Bill_Oddie ,  Bananaman  broadcastedBy  BBC ,  BBC  city  London   Output:   Home » News » Parenting » New Research Explores Reasons Why Teens Drink Alcohol  New Research Explores Reasons Why Teens Drink Alcohol  A new study examines the reasons why teens drink alcohol and finds that they do so for a variety of reasons, including experimentation, social acceptance, and coping with stress.  Researchers at the University of Pittsburgh Graduate School of Public Health surveyed more than 2,000 adolescents between the ages of 13 and 18 years old. The findings were published in the journal Addictive Behaviors.  "Understanding the motivations behind adolescent drinking is important because it can help us better target prevention efforts," said lead author Dr. Mark E. Courtney, Ph.D., M.P.H., associate professor in Pitt Public Health's Department of Behavioral and Community Health Sciences.  "For example, knowing that many adolescents drink to fit in with their peers could prompt schools to develop programs aimed at promoting healthy social norms around alcohol use."  Courtney and his colleagues found that over half of the adolescents reported having consumed alcohol at least once in their lives. Among those who drank, the most common reasons included curiosity or interest (67 percent), to have fun (64 percent), to relax or feel less anxious (58 percent), and to fit in or belong (57 percent).

Here is my code:  public static boolean isSorted(int[] arr){      return isSorted(arr,0,arr.length-1);  }  public static boolean isSorted(int[] arr, int start, int end){      if(start >= end){          return true;      }      if(arr[start] > arr[start+1]){          return false;      }      return isSorted(arr,start+1,end);  }  The problem with this code is that it returns true for arrays like {1,2,3,4,6}. Can someone tell me where I am going wrong?  A: You need to check the condition for all the elements between start and end.  This can be done by calling the method recursively for the subarray between start and end. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) administers the PHEP cooperative agreement on behalf of HHS. The research, published in the Journal of Adolescence, suggests that playing violent video games is associated with an increased likelihood of physical, verbal, and relational forms of bullying.  "Our findings suggest that parents, educators, and clinicians should consider whether exposure to violent video games might be contributing to bullying behaviors among adolescents," said lead author Jeffrey D. Hancock, Ph.D., associate professor of psychology at Brigham Young University.  "If so, limiting exposure to violent video games could be one way to reduce bullying."  Hancock and his colleagues analyzed data from the National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent to Adult Health, which followed a nationally representative sample of students in grades 7-12 from 1994-95 through 2008-09. Input:  Aleksandr_Prudnikov  birthDate  1989-02-24 ,  Aleksandr_Prudnikov  youthclub  FC_Spartak_Moscow ,  Aleksandr_Prudnikov  club  FC_Spartak_Moscow   Output:   Home > Journals > Arrow > ceaspp > Vol. 3 (2017) > Iss. 1  The Influence of Cultural Values on Corporate Social Responsibility Disclosure: Evidence from China  Jing Zhang, University of MacauFollow  Yuanyuan Chen, University of MacauFollow  This study investigates the influence of cultural values on corporate social responsibility (CSR) disclosure in the context of China. The sample consists of 165 Chinese A-share listed companies for the period of 2009–2013. Using the Hofstede's cultural dimensions theory, this study examines the relationship between cultural values and CSR disclosure. The results show that individualism is positively related to CSR disclosure, whereas uncertainty avoidance and masculinity are negatively related to CSR disclosure. This study contributes to the existing literature by providing empirical evidence on the impact of cultural values on CSR disclosure in the context of China.  Zhang, Jing and Chen, Yuanyuan (2017) "The Influence of Cultural Values on Corporate Social Responsibility Disclosure: Evidence from China," Communication, Economics and Strategic Planning Perspectives: Vol. 3 : Iss. 1 , Article 5.  DOI: 10.21423/

A vector image is an image represented by mathematical formulae for points lines curves and shapes rather than pixels or voxels which are used to represent raster graphics.Vector graphics are resolution-independent meaning that they can be scaled to any size without loss of quality.Vector graphics are resolution-independent meaning that they can be scaled to any size without loss of quality.In contrast raster graphics (also known as bitmap graphics) consist of a fixed grid of pixels where each pixel is assigned a color value. Input:  Bedford_Aerodrome  location  Thurleigh ,  Bedford_Aerodrome  icaoLocationIdentifier  EGBF ,  Thurleigh  postalCode  MK44 ,  Bedford_Aerodrome  operatingOrganisation  MotorSport_Vision ,  MotorSport_Vision  foundedBy  Peter_Ogden   Output:   Q: How to get data from Firebase database using AngularFire? I want to get data from my Firebase database using AngularFire. This is my code:  import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';  import { AngularFireDatabase, AngularFireList } from 'angularfire2/database';  @Component({    selector: 'app-root',    templateUrl: './app.component.html',    styleUrls: ['./app.component.css']  })  export class AppComponent implements OnInit {    users: AngularFireList<any[]>;    constructor(private db: AngularFireDatabase) { }    ngOnInit() {      this.users = this.db.list('/users');      this.users.subscribe(data => {        console.log(data);      });    }  }  The problem is that when I run this code, I get an error:  ERROR TypeError: Cannot read property 'subscribe' of undefined  What am I doing wrong here?  A: The list() method returns an AngularFireList instance, which doesn't have a subscribe() method. Instead you need to use the .valueChanges() observable to listen for changes to the list:  this.users = this.db.list('/users');

Input:  Ciudad_Ayala  populationMetro  1777539 ,  Ciudad_Ayala  leaderTitle  "City Manager" ,  Ciudad_Ayala  type  City   Output:   Home » News » Blog » What is the Difference Between a Residential Treatment Center and a Therapeutic Boarding School?  What is the Difference Between a Residential Treatment Center and a Therapeutic Boarding School?  When parents are faced with their teen's mental health issues, substance abuse, or behavioral problems, they often turn to residential treatment centers (RTC) or therapeutic boarding schools for help. However, these terms are often used interchangeably, leading to confusion about what each type of facility offers. In this article, we will explore the differences between a residential treatment center and a therapeutic boarding school to help parents make informed decisions about their child's care.  Residential Treatment Centers (RTC)  A residential treatment center (RTC) is a specialized facility designed to provide intensive, around-the-clock care for adolescents struggling with severe mental health disorders, substance abuse, or behavioral issues. These centers typically offer psychiatric care, individual and group therapy, medication management, and educational services. RTCs are licensed by the state and adhere to strict regulations regarding staffing, programming, and facilities. They often have higher staff-to-student ratios than therapeutic boarding schools, allowing for more individualized attention and support.  Therapeutic Boarding Schools  A therapeutic boarding school is a residential program that combines academic

Input:  It's_Great_to_Be_Young_(1956_film)  starring  John_Mills ,  It's_Great_to_Be_Young_(1956_film)  cinematography  Gilbert_Taylor ,  It's_Great_to_Be_Young_(1956_film)  runtime  94.0 ,  It's_Great_to_Be_Young_(1956_film)  gross  282838.0   Output:   The purpose of this study was to examine the relationship between self-efficacy and academic achievement among college students. This study used a quantitative research design. A convenience sample of 100 undergraduate students enrolled at a four-year public university in the southeastern region of the United States participated in this study. Participants completed the General Self-Efficacy Scale (Schwarzer & Jerusalem, 1995) and the Academic Self-Efficacy Scale (Pajares, 1996). Data were analyzed using descriptive statistics and Pearson product-moment correlation coefficients. Results indicated that there was a significant positive correlation between general self-efficacy and academic self-efficacy (r = .87, p < .001), and a significant positive correlation between academic self-efficacy and academic achievement (r = .42, p < .001). These findings suggest that self-efficacy is an important factor in academic achievement among college students. Implications for practice and future research are discussed.

The first column is used to input values, and the second column displays the result of a calculation based on the value in the first column. When the value in the first column changes, I want the background color of the cell in the first column to change temporarily (e.g., for 1 second) to indicate that the value has changed.  Is there a way to do this using Google Sheets scripting or another method?  A: You can achieve this by using the onEdit() function. Here is an example code:  function onEdit(e) {    var range = e.range;    if (range.getColumn() == 1 && range.getValue() != range.offset(0, 0).getValue()) { // Check if the edited cell is in column 1 and its value is different from the original value      range.setBackground("#FF0000"); // Set the background color to red for demonstration purposes      Utilities.sleep(1000); // Wait for 1 second      range.setBackground(""); // Reset the background color    }  }  In this example, we check if the edited cell is in column 1 (you can change it to match your needs) and if its value is different from the original value

I am trying to get a list of all files with .txt extension in a directory using Python.  I have tried this code:  import os  path = r'C:\Users\User\Desktop\Python\test'  files = [os.path.join(path, name) for name in os.listdir(path) if name.endswith('.txt')]  print(files)  But it returns an empty list.  Can someone help me understand what I am doing wrong here?  A: The problem is most likely that there are no files with .txt extension in the specified directory.  You can check this by changing your code to something like this:  import os  path = r'C:\Users\User\Desktop\Python\test'  files = [os.path.join(path, name) for name in os.listdir(path)]  print(f'All files in {path}: {files}')  files = [os.path.join(path, name) for name in os.listdir(path) if name.endswith('.txt')]  print(f'Files with .txt extension in {path}: {files}')  This will print all the files in the specified directory and then only the ones with .txt

I want to get the path of the current directory in Kotlin.  In Java, we can use System.getProperty("user.dir") to get the current directory path.  How can I do this in Kotlin?  A: In Kotlin, you can access the system properties using the kotlin.system.properties object.  So, to get the current directory path, you can use:  val currentDir = kotlin.system.properties["user.dir"]  A: The accepted answer is correct, but for Kotlin script files (.kts), you need to add import kotlin.system.* at the top of the file. Encryption Algorithms  Symmetric vs. Asymmetric Encryption  < Back Page 2 of 3 Next >  CompTIA Security+: Get Your Start in Cybersecurity (9L0-004) Guide to Exam Preparation and Practice  Encryption algorithms are mathematical formulas used to transform plaintext into ciphertext. An encryption algorithm can use either symmetric or asymmetric encryption. Symmetric encryption uses the same key for both encryption and decryption. Asymmetric encryption uses two keys: one for encryption and one for decryption.  The following sections describe some common encryption algorithms.  DES (Data Encryption Standard)  DES is a symmetric block cipher with a fixed block size of 64 bits and a variable key size of 40, 56, or 64 bits. DES was developed by IBM in the late 1960s and early 1970s and adopted as a standard by the National Bureau of Standards (NBS) in 1977. In 1998, DES was replaced by the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).  Triple DES (3DES)  Triple DES (3DES) is simply

Advocate Chaitanya Rohilla, appearing for the petitioner, submitted before the court that WhatsApp's new privacy policy is against the fundamental right to privacy guaranteed under Article 21 of the Constitution. Input:  Piotr_Hallmann  birthPlace  Gdynia,_Poland ,  Piotr_Hallmann  weight  70.308 ,  Gdynia,_Poland  timeZone  Central_European_Time   Output:   The purpose of this study was to examine the relationship between leadership styles and organizational commitment among nurses working in selected private hospitals in Ghana. The study adopted a descriptive survey research design. The population for the study consisted of all registered nurses working in three private hospitals in Accra, Ghana. A sample size of 150 respondents was obtained using stratified random sampling technique. Data were collected using self-administered questionnaires. The data collected were analyzed using descriptive statistics, Pearson product moment correlation, and multiple regression analysis. The results showed that transactional leadership style had a significant positive relationship with organizational commitment (r = .426, p < .05). Similarly, transformational leadership style also had a significant positive relationship with organizational commitment (r = .494, p < .05). The results of the multiple regression analysis revealed that both transactional and transformational leadership styles significantly predicted organizational commitment among nurses working in private hospitals in Accra, Ghana (R2 = .322, F (2, 147) = 22.272, p < .05). The study concluded that transactional and transformational leadership styles influence organizational commitment among nurses working in private hospitals in Accra, Ghana. It is recommended that hospital administrators should adopt transformational and transactional leadership styles to foster organizational commitment among nurses.

The report, based on a survey of more than 2,000 small business owners across the UK, US, Germany and the Netherlands, found that high-growth small businesses are twice as likely as other small businesses to have a written growth plan (47% vs. 23%). They are also more likely to invest in new technology (58% vs. 49%) and marketing (55% vs. 44%).  In the UK specifically, high-growth small businesses are twice as likely to have applied for external finance in the last two years (47% vs. 23%). The most common form of external finance sought by high-growth small businesses was a bank loan (43%), followed by a business credit card (28%), and an overdraft facility (24%). I am new to Angular JS. I want to add multiple fields with same name dynamically using Angular JS.  <input type="text" ng-model="firstName" name="firstName">  <input type="text" ng-model="lastName" name="lastName">  <input type="text" ng-model="age" name="age">  Here is my HTML code. I want to add multiple fields for firstName, lastName and age. How can I do this using Angular JS?  A: You can use ng-repeat directive to iterate over an array of objects which contain the properties you want to display. Something like this:  <div ng-repeat="item in items">      <input type="text" ng-model="item.firstName" name="firstName">      <input type="text" ng-model="item.lastName" name="lastName">      <input type="text" ng-model="item.age" name="age">  </div>  And in your controller:  $scope.items = [      {          firstName: '',          lastName: '',          age: ''      },      {          firstName: '',          lastName: '',          age: ''      }

In 2015, for the first time in history, there were more people aged 60 or over (901 million) than children under the age of five (697 million). By 2030, one in every six people will be over 60 years old. This trend has profound implications for health systems, economies and societies.  The number of people aged 60 or over is projected to more than double by 2050, reaching nearly 2.1 billion. At the same time, life expectancy continues to increase globally, reflecting improvements in nutrition, sanitation, housing, health care and living standards.  Ageing populations pose significant challenges for health systems. Non-communicable diseases such as cardiovascular disease, cancer, diabetes and chronic respiratory diseases – many of which are associated with ageing – are responsible for 7 out of every 10 deaths worldwide. They also account for 4 out of every 5 health expenditures globally.  In addition to the direct costs of treating non-communicable diseases, they impose indirect costs through reduced productivity, disability and informal care. Globally, the total economic cost of non-communicable diseases was estimated at US$ 7 trillion in 2011, equivalent to 12% of global GDP

In particular, he says, they have embraced fiscal austerity at precisely the wrong time, when the economy needs more stimulus, not less. Specifically, the study aimed to examine the following: (1) the extent to which teachers use technology in their teaching practices; (2) the factors that affect teachers' use of technology in their teaching practices; and (3) the role of professional development in enhancing teachers' use of technology in their teaching practices. Data were collected through document analysis, interviews, and questionnaires. A total of 75 respondents participated in the study: 15 school principals, 15 district supervisors, and 45 classroom teachers. Findings revealed that teachers in the participating countries used technology in various ways in their teaching practices. However, their use of technology was mostly at the lower levels of the Technology Integration Model developed by Koehler and Mishra (2008). Factors that affected teachers' use of technology in their teaching practices included availability of ICT resources, training and support, pedagogical content knowledge, teacher efficacy, and motivation. Professional development played a significant role in enhancing teachers' use of technology in their teaching practices. Recommendations for future research and practice were provided.

Input:  Lady_Anne_Monson  birthPlace  Darlington ,  Lady_Anne_Monson  birthDate  1726-01-01 ,  Lady_Anne_Monson  deathDate  1776-02-18   Output:   Home » Posts Tagged "Japan"  The Japanese Art of Kintsugi  Posted By Kate Morgan on Sep 25, 2015  Kintsugi is the Japanese art of repairing broken pottery with lacquer dusted or mixed with powdered gold, silver or platinum. The result is a piece that is more beautiful for having been broken. It is also known as kintsukuroi, meaning "golden repair". This ancient Japanese art form treats breakage and repair as part of the history of an object, rather than something to disguise. When an object is repaired by Kintsugi, the cracks and repairs are seen as part of its history and become part of its unique story. The philosophy behind Kintsugi is similar to the Buddhist concept of wabi-sabi, which celebrates imperfection, impermanence, and incompleteness. These philosophies teach us to accept the natural cycle of growth, decay, and death, and to see beauty in things that are flawed or damaged. Kintsugi teaches us to embrace our own imperfections and to see them as part of what makes us unique and beautiful. In a world that often values perfection and tries to hide or fix flaws, Kintsugi offers a different perspective. It encourages us to see the beauty in brokenness and to honour the

Make Use of Vertical Space  One of the easiest ways to create more storage space in your kitchen is to make use of vertical space. Instead of cramming everything onto your countertops or cabinets, consider installing shelves or racks on your walls. You can use these shelves to store dishes, pots, pans, and other items that you use frequently.  2. Install Pull-Out Shelves  Pull-out shelves are another great way to maximize storage space in your kitchen. These shelves can be installed in base cabinets and pantry cupboards, making it easy to access hard-to-reach items without having to bend over or strain your back.  3. Add a Lazy Susan  If you have corner cabinets, consider adding a lazy Susan to make the most of this often-wasted space. A lazy Susan is a rotating shelf that makes it easy to access items stored in the back of the cabinet.  4. Invest in a Pantry  If you have the space, consider adding a pantry to your kitchen. A pantry is a great place to store

Zak Bentley  The International Finance Corporation (IFC), the private sector arm of the World Bank Group, has invested $20 million in Orient Green Power Company (OGPC), a subsidiary of India's Orient Paper & Industries, to support the development of wind power projects in India.  As part of the investment, IFC will also acquire a 9.9 percent equity stake in OGPC, which is currently building a 45MW wind power project in the state of Karnataka. The company plans to develop up to 500MW of wind power capacity in India over the next five years.  According to IFC, India's installed wind power capacity reached 17GW at the end of 2012, making it the fourth largest wind power market in the world. By Tibbetts Brooks  According to the SEC's complaint, filed in U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, First Investors Management Company Inc. failed to disclose to some of its mutual fund clients that it was receiving revenue sharing payments from affiliated broker-dealers in connection with the sale of the mutual funds. The SEC alleges that First Investors also failed to disclose that it had entered into fee offset arrangements with the affiliated broker-dealers, which resulted in the clients effectively paying higher advisory fees than they were led to believe.  The SEC's complaint charges First Investors with violating Sections 206(2) and 206(4) of the Investment Advisers Act of 1940 and Rule 206(4)-8 thereunder. The SEC seeks disgorgement of ill-gotten gains plus prejudgment interest, civil penalties, and permanent injunctions against future violations of the securities laws.  Tagged:

Input:  Ciudad_Ayala  timeZone  Pacific_Standard_Time_Zone   Output:   Q: How do I make a program that prints out the number of occurrences of each letter in a string? For example, if the string is "hello world", the output should be something like this:  e: 0  h: 2  l: 3  o: 1  r: 1  d: 1  w: 1  A: You can use collections.Counter for this:  from collections import Counter  def count_letters(string):      counts = Counter(string)      for letter, count in counts.items():          print(f"{letter}: {count}")  Example:  string = "hello world"  count_letters(string)  Output:  h: 2  e: 0  l: 3  o: 1  w: 1  r: 1  d: 1  A: You can create a dictionary to keep track of how many times each character appears in the string.  text = "hello world"  counts = {}  for char in text:      if char in counts:          counts[char] += 1      else:          counts[char] = 1  for key, value in counts.items():      print(f"{key}: {value}")  Output:  h:

Input:  Bedford_Aerodrome  operatingOrganisation  MotorSport_Vision ,  Bedford_Aerodrome  location  Thurleigh ,  Bedford_Aerodrome  icaoLocationIdentifier  EGBF   Output:   Q: how to use "if" statement with "for" loop in python? I am trying to write a program that calculates the sum of even numbers between 1-100 using for loop and if statement.  Here is my code:  sum = 0  for i in range(1, 101):      if i % 2 == 0:          sum += i  print(sum)  This code works fine, but I want to improve it by adding an if statement inside the for loop. Like this:  sum = 0  for i in range(1, 101):      if i % 2 == 0:          sum += i          if sum > 100:              break  print(sum)  However, when I run this code, it doesn't give me the expected result (4950). Instead, it gives me the sum of all the numbers between 1-100, not just the even numbers.  Can someone explain why this happens and suggest a way to fix it?  A: Your inner if statement is checking if the sum is greater than 100, so once the sum reaches 100 or more, the loop will exit. However, since you are still iterating over all the numbers from 1 to 100, the loop will continue to add

Input:  Abraham_A._Ribicoff  spouse  "Ruth Ribicoff" ,  Abraham_A._Ribicoff  successor  Anthony_J._Celebrezze ,  Abraham_A._Ribicoff  birthPlace  United_States ,  United_States  ethnicGroup  African_Americans   Output:   Q: How to write this SQL query more efficiently? I have a table named users with columns id, username, email, password, created_at, updated_at.  I want to select all rows where updated_at is less than 30 days ago.  This is my current query:  SELECT * FROM users WHERE DATE(updated_at) < DATE(DATEADD(day, -30, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP()))  Is there a more efficient way to write this query?  Note: I'm using MariaDB.  A: The best way to optimize queries is to use indexes.  In your case, you can create an index on the updated_at column.  CREATE INDEX idx_users_updated_at ON users (updated_at);  After creating the index, your query will perform much faster.  You can also rewrite your query as follows:  SELECT * FROM users WHERE updated_at < DATEADD(day, -30, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP())  Since MySQL/MariaDB automatically converts datetime values to date when used in comparisons.

The Digital Standards for Trade is a free online platform designed to make it easier for SMEs to comply with international trade rules and procedures. It provides access to over 50 internationally recognised standards and guidelines developed by ICC and its global network of national committees.  "Small and medium-sized enterprises are the backbone of the global economy," said ICC Secretary General, World Chambers Federation Executive Director and Digital Standards for Trade Steering Committee Chair, John Denton AO. "Yet many SMEs lack the resources and expertise needed to overcome the myriad of challenges they face when trading across borders. This new digital tool will help level the playing field by providing immediate access to the technical know-how required to participate in international trade." In a large zip-top plastic bag, combine the soy sauce, sherry, brown sugar, garlic, gingerroot, and red pepper flakes. Add chicken; seal bag and turn to coat. Refrigerate for at least 2 hours.  Drain and discard marinade. In a large nonstick skillet coated with cooking spray, stir-fry chicken in batches over medium heat until no longer pink. Remove and keep warm.  In the same skillet, stir-fry broccoli and snow peas in remaining marinade until crisp-tender. Return chicken to the pan. Stir in cashews and green onions. Cook and stir until heated through. Serve over rice. Yield: 4 servings.

I am trying to change the background color of a cell in Excel using VBA. Here is my code:  Sub ColorCell()      Range("A1").Select      ActiveCell.Interior.ColorIndex = 6  End Sub  However, when I run this code, nothing happens. Can someone please help me understand what I am doing wrong?  A: The select statement is not necessary.  Sub ColorCell()      With Range("A1")          .Interior.ColorIndex = 6      End With  End Sub  Or even simpler:  Sub ColorCell()      Range("A1").Interior.ColorIndex = 6  End Sub  A: Your code works for me. Make sure you have a reference to Microsoft Excel Object Library in your VBA project.  To add a reference:  *  *Go to Tools > References in the VBA Editor  *Check if Microsoft Excel x.x Object Library is ticked  *If not, click Browse, navigate to C:\Program Files (x86)\Common Files\Microsoft Shared\VBA\VBAx.x\VBAx.x\Excelx.x.x.x.x.x.x.x.x

How can I create a website for my business?  By: Chris Hogan - Updated: 20 Dec 2012 | *Discuss  The internet is one of the most powerful marketing tools available to businesses today. Whether your business is small or large, local or national, having a website is essential if you want to reach out to potential customers. Creating a website for your business doesn't have to be difficult or expensive. In fact, there are several ways you can do it yourself with little or no technical knowledge required.  Choose a Domain Name  The first step in creating a website for your business is choosing a domain name. This is the address people will type into their web browser to visit your site. Your domain name should be easy to remember, short and ideally related to your business. For example, if your business is called 'John's Plumbing', a good domain name might be johnsplumbing.com.  To register a domain name, you'll need to find a domain registrar. There are many reputable registrars to choose from, including GoDaddy, 123-reg and Network Solutions. The cost of registering a domain name varies depending on the registrar and the length of time you want to register it for. Prices typically start at around £5 per year.

I am trying to set up a static IP address for my wireless network adapter so that I can connect to a VPN. However, when I go to the Network and Sharing Center and click on Change Adapter Settings, I don't see any option to change the settings for my wireless network adapter. Can someone please help me with this?  A: To set a static IP address for your wireless network adapter, follow these steps:  1. Press the Windows key + R to open the Run dialog box, type "ncpa.cpl" and press Enter. This will open the Network Connections window.  2. Find your wireless network adapter in the list of available network connections. It should have a Wi-Fi icon next to it. Right-click on it and select "Properties".  3. In the Properties window, select "Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4)" or "Internet Protocol Version 6 (TCP/IPv6)" depending on your network configuration. Click on the "Properties" button.  4. In the Internet Protocol Properties window, select "Use the following IP address" and enter the desired static IP address, subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS server(s).  5. Click "OK" to save the changes.  6. Restart your computer

What is the Difference Between Acupuncture and Acupressure?  Acupuncture and acupressure are both ancient healing practices that originated in China over 2,000 years ago. Both therapies are based on the principles of Traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM) and aim to restore balance and harmony to the body by stimulating specific points along the body's energy pathways, known as meridians. However, there are some key differences between these two modalities.  Acupuncture involves the insertion of thin, sterile needles into specific acupuncture points along the body's meridians. The needles are typically left in place for 15-30 minutes, during which time they may be gently manipulated to enhance their therapeutic effect. Acupuncture is often used to treat a wide range of conditions, including pain, stress, anxiety, insomnia, digestive issues, and more.  Acupressure, on the other hand, involves applying pressure to acupuncture points using the fingers, thumbs, or sometimes special tools. This pressure can be applied for several minutes to stimulate the point and promote healing. Acupressure can be self-administered or performed by a trained practitioner. It is often used to

I am using Yeoman to build my AngularJS app. When I run grunt serve, it starts a server on port 9000 but doesn't open the browser for me. How do I get it to open the browser with localhost:9000?  A: There is no way to do this by default. But you can create your own custom task which will start the server and then open the browser. PersonX is always the subject of the event. You have to determine whether the Head can be characterized by being or having the Tail or not. I am trying to create a figure with four subplots arranged in a 2x2 grid. However, I want the bottom-right subplot to be at the top-left, and the top-left subplot to be at the bottom-right. Is there a way to do this in matplotlib?  Here is my current code:  import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2)  axs[0, 0].plot(range(10))  axs[0, 1].plot(range(10))  axs[1, 0].plot(range(10))  axs[1, 1].plot(range(10))  plt.show()  This produces a figure with the subplots arranged in the default order (top-left, top-right, bottom-left, bottom-right). How can I switch the positions of the top-left and bottom-right subplots?  A: One way to do this is to use the rearrange_axes function from the seaborn library. This function allows you to rearrange the subplots after they have been created.  First, install seaborn if you haven't already

By John Manganaro  The high court's decision effectively leaves intact the PTE 84-24, which allows financial services firms to receive compensation for providing investment advice to retirement plans and individual retirement accounts (IRAs) without running afoul of the Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) and the Internal Revenue Code's prohibited transaction rules.  The DOL first issued PTE 84-24 in 1984 to address concerns that certain transactions between plan fiduciaries and service providers could result in conflicts of interest. Since its initial issuance, the PTE has been amended several times, most recently in 2005.  In June 2014, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit upheld the validity of PTE 84-24, rejecting arguments made by the

Here is our list of the top 10 Christmas markets in Europe.  Christmas markets are popping up all over the world, but nothing compares to the original German Christmas markets. The oldest market dates back to 1384 and can still be visited today in Dresden. Germany has more than 50 traditional Christmas markets, each with its own unique charm. Munich's Christkindlmarkt is one of the most popular ones, with almost six million visitors every year.  The Christmas market in Strasbourg is considered to be the oldest Christmas market in Europe. It was first mentioned in 1570 and takes place in the heart of the historic city center. During the festive season, the streets are filled with the smell of mulled wine, gingerbread, and roasted chestnuts. More than 300 wooden chalets sell everything from handcrafted souvenirs to local delicacies.  The Christmas market in Vienna is located in front of the City Hall and attracts around 2.5 million visitors every year. Input:  Alan_B._Miller_Hall  architect  Robert_A._M._Stern ,  Alan_B._Miller_Hall  address  "101 Ukrop Way" ,  Alan_B._Miller_Hall  buildingStartDate  "30 March 2007" ,  Alan_B._Miller_Hall  currentTenants  Mason_School_of_Business ,  Alan_B._Miller_Hall  location  Virginia ,  Alan_B._Miller_Hall  owner  College_of_William_&_Mary   Output:   Home > News > featured news > Mitsubishi Electric Completes Acquisition of ICONICS  Mitsubishi Electric Completes Acquisition of ICONICS  Mitsubishi Electric | January 05, 2022  Mitsubishi Electric Corporation announced today that it has completed the acquisition of ICONICS, a global provider of industrial automation software headquartered in Foxborough, Massachusetts, USA. The acquisition is part of Mitsubishi Electric's strategy to strengthen its digital solutions business for the factory automation (FA) and energy business sectors.  With this acquisition, Mitsubishi Electric will integrate ICONICS' advanced human-machine interface (HMI), supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), operations management system (OMS), and Internet of Things (IoT) technologies into its FA and energy businesses. This will enable Mitsubishi Electric to offer more comprehensive solutions to customers by integrating HMI, SCADA, OMS, and IoT with Mitsubishi Electric's own PLCs, servo systems, robotics, visualization devices, and energy management systems. How do I check if a string is in uppercase or lowercase in C++?  A: Here's a simple way to do it using std::all_of:  #include <iostream>  #include <string>  #include <algorithm>  int main()  {      std::string str = "abc";      bool isUpperCase = std::all_of(str.begin(), str.end(), [](char c) { return std::isupper(c); });      bool isLowerCase = std::all_of(str.begin(), str.end(), [](char c) { return std::islower(c); });      std::cout << (isUpperCase ? "Upper case" : "Not upper case") << std::endl;      std::cout << (isLowerCase ? "Lower case" : "Not lower case") << std::endl;  }  Output:  Not upper case  Not lower case  A: You can use std::all_of with std::isupper or std::islower:  #include <iostream>  #include <string>  #include <algorithm>  #include <cctype>  int main()  {      std::string str = "ABC

Input:  Olga_Bondareva  almaMater  Leningrad_State_University ,  Olga_Bondareva  birthPlace  Leningrad,_USSR ,  Olga_Bondareva  professionalField  Economics ,  Olga_Bondareva  professionalField  Mathematics   Output:   Q: How to set up DNS for multiple subdomains pointing to different IP addresses? I have a domain name example.com and I want to create two subdomains mail.example.com and app.example.com.  mail.example.com should point to one IP address (192.168.0.1) and app.example.com should point to another IP address (192.168.0.2).  How can I set up my DNS records to achieve this?  A: You need to create two CNAME records:  *  *One for mail.example.com with value mail.server.example.com  *One for app.example.com with value app.server.example.com  And then create two A records:  *  *One for mail.server.example.com with value 192.168.0.1  *One for app.server.example.com with value 192.168.0.2  Note: server.example.com is just an example hostname, you can use anything you want.  In some cases, you might need to add a wildcard record *.example.com to prevent other subdomains from breaking.

Input:  Roadside_Attractions  foundingYear  2003-01-01   Output:   Home » News » Parenting » Marijuana Use During Pregnancy Linked to ADHD Symptoms in Children  Marijuana Use During Pregnancy Linked to ADHD Symptoms in Children  By Traci Pedersen  A new study finds that women who use marijuana during pregnancy are more likely to have children with attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) symptoms.  Researchers at Columbia University's Mailman School of Public Health analyzed data from the National Epidemiologic Survey on Alcohol and Related Conditions (NESARC), which included 36,344 adults aged 18 years and older interviewed between 2001-2002 and 2004-2005.  They found that women who reported using marijuana during pregnancy were 37 percent more likely to have children with ADHD symptoms compared to women who did not use marijuana during pregnancy. The association was stronger among women who used marijuana heavily during pregnancy.  "We know that prenatal exposure to tobacco, alcohol, cocaine, and opioids is associated with adverse neurodevelopmental outcomes," said Dr. Katherine Manthey, Ph.D., M.P.H., lead author of the study.  "Our study adds to the growing body of literature suggesting that prenatal marijuana exposure is also associated with adverse neurodevelopmental outcomes."

PersonX is always the subject of the event. You have to determine whether the Head happens before the Tail or not. Classify your answers into "Yes" and "No". In the section about intelligence, the author says that the human mind "sorts outnumerous inputs to select those that appear to make most coherent sense as a unified first explanation of reality", which sounds plausible until you realize that this is exactly what scientific theories do. The author claims that the book provides "a unified conceptual framework for understanding our experiences and the world around us", but nowhere does he provide any such thing. That said, the book is full of interesting tidbits about how the mind perceives the world, along with some errors (genes are not stored in the nucleus of the cell - they are DNA, and DNA is found in the nucleus), and over-simplifications and/or omissions that undermine many of the arguments he presents. I'm sorry I spent the money on this book. Too bad you can't return books after you've actually read them. I have a script that checks how many times a specific word appears in a column in a csv file. The problem is that the file is quite large and the script takes too long to run. Is there a way to make it more efficient?  import csv  from collections import Counter  with open('file.csv', newline='') as csvfile:      reader = csv.reader(csvfile)      next(reader)      data = list(reader)  word = 'specific_word'  count = 0  for row in data:      if word in row[0]:          count += 1  print(count)  A: This can be made faster by using pandas library. It has a built-in function called value_counts() that counts the number of occurrences of each unique value in a Series or DataFrame.  First, install pandas using pip:  pip install pandas  Then, modify your code as follows:  import pandas as pd  df = pd.read_csv('file.csv')  count = df[df.iloc[:, 0].str.contains(word)].shape[0]  print(count)  Here, iloc[:, 0] selects the first column of the DataFrame, str.

The output should look like this:      col1 col2 col3  0     A    1    X  2     B    2    Z  4     C    3    W  How can I achieve this? Every year, millions of tons of plastic waste end up in our oceans, harming marine life and polluting our environment. In response to this crisis, there has been a growing demand for eco-friendly alternatives to traditional plastic packaging. Here are some sustainable options that are gaining popularity:  1. Paper: Paper is a versatile and biodegradable material that can be used for various types of packaging. It can be sourced from sustainably managed forests and is easily recyclable. Paper packaging is commonly used for products such as food, cosmetics, and household items.  2. Bamboo: Bamboo is a fast-growing, renewable resource that can be used to create strong and durable packaging materials. It is biodegradable and compostable, making it an excellent alternative to single-use plastics. Bamboo packaging is often used for food, cosmetics, and personal care products.  3. Bioplastics: Bioplastics are made from renewable sources such as cornstarch, sugarcane, and other plant-based materials. They offer many of the same benefits as traditional plastics, but they are biodegradable and compostable. Biop

In users table there is a field named "user_id" and in user_details table there is a field named "user_id".  Now I want to retrieve data from user_details table where user_id = $this->Session->read('Auth.User.id')  How can I do this?  A: In your User model, you need to define hasOne relation with UserDetails model.  class User extends AppModel {      public $hasOne = array(          'UserDetails' => array(              'className' => 'UserDetails',              'foreignKey' => 'user_id',              'dependent' => false          )      );  }  Then in your controller, you can use containable behavior to load related data.  $this->User->find('all', array(      'contain' => array(          'UserDetails'      )  ));  This will load all Users along with their related UserDetails.  You can also specify condition for UserDetails using conditions key.  $this->User->find('all', array(      'contain' => array(          'UserDetails' => array(              'conditions' => array(                  'UserDetails

This book has been getting a lot of buzz lately, and for good reason. It's a quick read, but packs a powerful punch.  The premise of the book is that there is a right way and a wrong way to organize your home. Most people approach organization with the mentality of "less is more," which means they try to get rid of as many things as possible. In contrast, Kondo suggests that you keep everything that "sparks joy" within you, and only discard items that do not.  Kondo argues that if you follow her method, you will never have to tidy again. She explains that most people don't really enjoy organizing their homes, so they put it off until it gets out of control, and then they spend hours trying to fix it all at once. By following her method, however, you will actually enjoy the process of sorting through your belongings, because you will be surrounded by things that make you happy.  One of the biggest takeaways from this book for me was the idea of thanking each item before deciding whether or not to keep it. When you thank something for the role it played in your life, it becomes much easier to let go of it if it no longer sparks joy.  For example,

White was born in Chicago and studied at the Art Institute of Chicago and later at the Art Students League in New York City. He is considered one of the most important African-American artists of the 20th century.  White's art is known for its powerful social commentary, focusing on issues such as racism, poverty, and segregation. He often depicted African-American subjects, portraying them with dignity and strength. Many of his works were inspired by historical events and figures, as well as by everyday life in African-American communities.  White worked in various mediums, including drawing, painting, printmaking, and sculpture. His style can be described as a combination of realism and modernism, with strong influences from African and African-American art traditions.  Throughout his career, White received numerous awards and honors, including a Guggenheim Fellowship, and his works are held in many prestigious collections, including the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Museum of Modern Art, and the Smithsonian American Art Museum.  Charles White played a significant role in promoting social justice and raising awareness about the African-American experience through his powerful and evocative artwork.

The generated questions should be open-ended and not easily answerable with a single word or a phrase.  Passage: In a village, there are 200 houses. Each house has an average of 3 people living in it. How many people live in total in the village?  In the village, if there are 200 houses and each house has an average of 3 people living in it, to find the total number of people living in the village, we can multiply the total number of houses by the average number of people per house.  So, the calculation would be 200 houses * 3 people/house.  Therefore, there are 600 people living in total in the village (200 houses * 3 people/house = 600 people).The answer is: 600

I am new to web development and I am trying to set up a local web server to test my work before pushing it to production. I have installed XAMPP on my windows machine but when I try to access http://localhost/ in my browser, it says "This site can't be reached". What am I doing wrong?  A: Make sure your XAMPP control panel is running and all the services (Apache, MySQL, etc.) are started. Then try again.  Also, make sure you don't have any firewalls blocking the port 80 (http) or 443 (https).  Finally, check if another application is already using port 80. You can do this by running the command netstat -an | findstr :80 in the command prompt. If there is something listening on port 80, you will need to either stop that application or change the port used by XAMPP.  To change the port used by Apache in XAMPP, open the file xampp\apache\conf\httpd.conf and search for the line Listen 80. Replace 80 with the port you want to use (e.g. Listen 8080). Then save the file and restart the Apache service via the XAMPP control panel.

A: You can use LINQ to achieve this:  var result = myList.FirstOrDefault(x => x["name"] == "A")?.["id"];  This will return the first dictionary from the list where the value of the key "name" is equal to "A", then access the value of the key "id" from that dictionary.  If there is no such dictionary in the list, the result will be null. For your Student class, you haven't defined a __repr__ method, so Python falls back to calling the __str__ method. Since you haven't defined that either, Python tries to convert the object to a string by iterating over its attributes, which fails because your Student object isn

Input:  Imagine_(John_Lennon_song)  musicalArtist  John_Lennon   Output:   Home » News » Press Releases  DHS S&T Awards $1 Million to Develop Cybersecurity Tools for Small Businesses  The Department of Homeland Security (DHS) Science and Technology Directorate (S&T) has awarded $1 million to Carnegie Mellon University's Software Engineering Institute (SEI) to develop cybersecurity tools for small businesses.  This project is part of DHS S&T's Cybersecurity for Small Business (CSB) program, which focuses on increasing the cyber resilience of small businesses through education, outreach, and technology development.  "Small businesses are the backbone of the U.S. economy," said William N. Bryan, Senior Official Performing the Duties of the Under Secretary for Science and Technology. "But they often lack the resources to adequately protect themselves against cyber threats. This project will help level the playing field by providing them with affordable, easy-to-use cybersecurity tools."  The SEI team will develop two cybersecurity tools for small businesses: a vulnerability scanner and a security incident response tool. The vulnerability scanner will assess the cybersecurity posture of a small business's IT systems and recommend cost-effective remediation measures. The security incident response tool will help small businesses detect, respond to, and recover from cybersecurity incidents. Both tools will be designed to be user-friendly and cost-effective

The Game Gear primarily competed with Nintendo's Game Boy, the Atari Lynx and NEC's TurboExpress in its attempt to become the dominant handheld console of the 16-bit era, but it was not as successful as its rival, the Game Boy, and it struggled to maintain exclusivity due to the increasing trend of multiplatform games. By late 1992, the Game Gear's lack of third-party software support effectively made it obsolete, and in North America Sega stopped producing new titles for the system in 1993. In Japan, however, first-party releases continued until 1997, with third-party titles coming as late as 1999.  - A role-playing video game (commonly referred to as role-playing game or RPG, and in the past was also known as computer role-playing game or CRPG) is a video game genre where the player controls the actions of a character (and/or several party members) immersed in some well-defined world. Solve -47*d + 8 = -45*d for d.  To solve the equation -47*d + 8 = -45*d for d, follow these steps:  Step 1: Isolate the variable 'd' by moving all terms containing 'd' to one side of the equation and constants to the other side.  To do this, add 47*d to both sides of the equation:  -47*d + 47*d + 8 = -45*d + 47*d  This simplifies to:  8 = 2*d  Step 2: Solve for 'd' by isolating it.  To do this, divide both sides of the equation by 2:  8 / 2 = 2*d / 2  This simplifies to:  4 = d  So, the solution to the equation is d = 4.

The initiative aims to promote sustainable urban mobility by encouraging people to change their travel habits and use cleaner and healthier modes of transport such as walking, cycling or public transport.  In Monaco, the Department of Urban Planning, Mobility and Sustainable Development has organised various events throughout the week to raise awareness among residents and visitors about the importance of sharing public spaces with pedestrians.  On Monday, 17th September, a stand was set up at the Condamine Market to present the City's initiatives for sustainable mobility, including the new bike-sharing service, the extension of the Portier car park, the development of the bus network and the implementation of parking meters.  On Wednesday, 19th September, a seminar was held at the Grimaldi Forum on the subject of "Walkability", attended by local authorities, experts and professionals in the fields of urban planning and mobility. Input:  McVeagh_of_the_South_Seas  imdbId  0004319 ,  McVeagh_of_the_South_Seas  writer  Harry_Carey_(actor_born_1878)   Output:   The purpose of this study is to evaluate the efficacy and safety of intravenous (IV) administration of ACE-083 for the treatment of patients with mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease (AD).  This is a Phase 2, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, multi-center study designed to evaluate the efficacy and safety of intravenous (IV) administration of ACE-083 for the treatment of patients with mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease (AD). Patients will be randomized to receive either ACE-083 or placebo via IV infusion once every two weeks for 52 weeks. In addition, patients will also receive open-label donepezil hydrochloride (Aricept®) at a stable dose for the duration of the study.  Patients will be screened for eligibility approximately 28 days prior to the start of the study. During the screening period, patients will undergo medical history review, physical examination, laboratory tests, neuropsychological assessments, brain magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), electrocardiogram (ECG), and cardiac telemetry monitoring.  Patients who meet all inclusion criteria and do not meet any exclusion criteria will be enrolled into the study and will enter a 6-week single-blind, placebo lead-in period.

By P&I Staff  (Bloomberg) — The board of the $445 billion California Public Employees' Retirement System (CalPERS) voted unanimously to reject a shareholder proposal filed by Arjuna Capital calling on BlackRock to disclose how it is managing climate-related financial risks across its investment portfolios.  In a statement, CalPERS said it believes the proposal is unnecessary because BlackRock has already adopted many of the requested measures.  BlackRock CEO Larry Fink announced last month that the asset manager will make sustainability integral to its investment process and product offerings. As part of the changes, BlackRock will exit investments in companies that generate more than 25% of their revenues from thermal coal production.  "We believe BlackRock's recent announcement demonstrates that they understand the importance of addressing climate risk," said Rob Feckner
